 France meet her problem.\nThe whole plan la submitted to tinGermans,\nwho will be Invited to London\nFebruary 28 to glvo their answer.\nGermany's Answer Known.\nGermany's answer to the note containing\nthe allied demand, which will be.\nsent out In a few days. Is already\nknown. It will be a flat refusal, and,\nInasmuch as the tax feature Is entirely\noutside the treaty, the refusal can\neasily bring back matters to where they\nstarted.\nGermany's point blank refusal is foreshadowed\nby a statement made this\nmorning from the most reliable source j\nof German Information available to The i\nNew York Herald.\n\"The plan is absolutely impossible,\" j\nthis authority said. \"No Germnn Gov- i\nemment accepting It could escape revolution.\nThe highest estimate of Germany's\ncapacity to pay annually does\nnot exceed 1,750,000,000 marks gold,\neven If Germany Is allowed to retain\nupper Silesia and the Allies retrocede a\nsubstantial merchant tonnage.\"\nGermany's refusal probably will bo\nmade known when the Brussels conference\nof experts resumes, on February 7,\nIts Investigations Into Germany's conditions.\nIn Inside British circles there\nla not the slightest expectation that\nGermany will ever pay a reduced sum\nof the tax. Some, value, they believe,\nmay attach to. the flrat annuities, but\nafter that the whole thin* la too problematical\nfor the Brltiah to consider It\nIn their own future plane. But to\nFrance the discount value of theae annuities\nfor many yeara to come, should j\nGdrrnany accept, la vital, and even the\nFrench admit that discount Is impossible\nunless all the Allies Indorse Germany's\nplcd*e.\nIT. I. Cooperation Kaaentlal.\nIn the adoption of the reparations plan\nAmerica has not been consulted, and if\nAnier.ca'p. views *?.re learned hero at\nall It was through Sir Auckland Geddea.\nThis despite the recognition that America's\ncooperation Is absolutely essential\nIf the German obligations ire to be\nTranced.\nTo-day'a action presages a political\ncl'Date noil menu), invomnn ne nic i\nof the Brland MtnlHtry, and vegcr* are\nbeing made, with odds at eight to five,\nthat It will fall. i A Cabinet headed by\nRaymond Polncare could repudiate the\nwhole scheme, but at the peril now of a\ndefinite break In the alliance with the\nBritish.\nAt best France during the first two t\nyears will receive the equivalent of I,-'\n000,000,000 .paper francs. Inasmuch as\nBelgium's priority Is 2,500,000,000 marks\non Germany's payments. With this1\nFrance- will be expected to meet her\ngrowing budget deficit of more than\n11,000,000,000 francs. Counting the export\ntax on the basis of the figures for\n1 #12. France's part of all German payments\nwill not exceed 1(0,000,000,000\nmarks gold, against her total pensions\nand damages of 1,500,000,000,000 francs.\nThe United States may formally protest\nagainst the Allies Imposing an export\ntax on Germany without first consulting\nher as being a violation of her\nrights which the Knox resolution affirms\nIt not cblng overlooked here, the\neffect being to raise the prices of United\nContinued on Third Pngr.\nGOOD Morning! Turn in 'Telephone filree- I\ntory of Home and Business Nerds,\" Heptlon\nSix to-day's Issue. Note the ninny ads of\nhorns, office and factory necessities st bar-\ngain prices Adv.\nh\nu.)\n\"l92, (651)9^7/\n'RECAST m i\nir fair and much ^1^1\nnth winds. I I\nday, 41; lowest, 31,\n>e found on pagu 21.\n3?DAILY. v\nHOUSE ACCEPTS\nLONDON HOM1\n\nSocial Despatch to Tit\n\nACCEPTANCE by the United Si\nhome of J. P. Morgan in Londor\nAmbassador was approved by the Hi\nof the whole. The action was taken\nmatic and consular appropriation b\nwith little debate.\nUnder House rules the action i\nby the House proper later, but ind:\nraised. The section authorizing 1\nnnf nf fhn Kill An o nninf\nposal meets with almost unanimous i\nThe proposal has been pending\nyears. Its acceptance was urged by\nCongress and again by the State D\nthe House Foreign Affairs Committ*\nCommittee recently reported a reso\nit is probable this will be abandonet\nHouse appropriation bill accomplish\nRepresentative Rogers (Mak)\nin explaining this section of the n\nMr. Morgan for making the offer ai\nning of a movement by Congress to\nthe Ambassadors in other countries\nThe House agreed also to an i\n5150,000 for the purchase of an Am\nThe Morgan house in London\nassociated with the Morgans for thr\nbered by the people of London as tl\nof J. Pierpont Morgan, father of.th\ni _\nUNIONS WILL FIGHT\nCUT IN RAIL WAGES\n'Will Not Peacefully Submit,'\nSays Statement From Three\nBiff Brotherhoods.\nI\nDENY BREAK IN H. C. OF L. j\nBusiness Depression Brought\nOn to Aid Propaganda,\nCharges W. G. Lee.\nCleveland, Jan. 29.?Heads of three j1\nbig railroad brotherhoods in formal j\nstatement* here to-night said the rail-\nroad men of the country \"will not\npeaceably submit\" to the wage reductions\nwhich Chicago despatches say\nthe railways will seek from the United\nStates Railway Labor Board in a petl- 1\ntion to be presented Monday.\nW. G. Lee, president of the Brotherhood\nof Railroad Trainmen; W. S.\nCarter, president of the Brotherhood\nof Locomotive Firemen and Enginemen,\nand L. K. Sheppard, president of\nthe Order of Railway Conductors, 1\nmade this declaration in formal state- j\nments. A similar declaration was\nmade Thursday by Warren S. Stone,\ngrand chief of the Brotherhood of Lo- i\ncomotive Engineers. 1\nAll the brotherhood executives declare I\nthat reports of decreases In the cost of 1\nliving are not borne out by actual con- 1\ndltlona. but are the result of propaganda;\nthat the wages of railway cm-\nployees did not increase as rapidly as 1\ndid the cost of living, or as much, and I\nthat railway men are not now receiving\nas high a standard of wages aa are paid\nin many other Industries.\nMr. Lee asserted that in his opinion i\n\"sonic, if jiot the greater portion, of the- J\nbusiness depression has been brought\nabout solely for the purpose of prejudicing\nthe public in the Interest of a reduction\nin wages generally.\"\nMr. Carter declared that \"notwithstanding\nall the wage Increases made\neither by the Railroad Administration\nor the iAbor Board, It can be shown\nthat because of the great Increase In\nthe efficiency of railroad employees\nthere has been no practical Increase In\nwage costs compared with product.\" Mr.\nSheppard asserted that \"to admit\nthat In this country of ours It Is necessary\nto make an onsluught on- labor at\nthis time, after all the country has done\nfor the railroads, is absolutely unAmerican,\"\nMessrs. Lee, Carter and Sheppard also\npolntod out that the railway employee Is\na piece worker, laid off and not paid\nwhen railroad traffic Is light.\nRAIL HEADS PLAN\nTHREE LINES OF BATTLE\nPublicity First Weapon in i\nLower Wage Fight.\nDetails of the plan formulated by railroad\nexecutives In their flght for a lower J\nwage scale for employees became known\nyesterday, following -the announcement 1\non Friday that tho step had been decided\non. There la to bo a publicity campaign\nIn which It has boon planned to take the I\nowner*' ca*e straight to the people of I\nthe country and ahow them In-detail, the\natralta In which the roada And them- j s\nelvc* becauae of Increased coat*.\nA second angle of the campaign will\nbe the fight to be wagol before the i\nUnited Htate* Hailroad Labor Hoard. I\nwhich I* In session now In Chicago, and\nthe third will be an open war with or- I\nganlzed labor. These arc the three main\nline* along which the battle will be i r\nfought.\nThe Initial volley of publicity I* ex-\npeoted to-morrow. Preparation for the\ncampaign on the other line* is going j\nalong smoothly.' Member* of the labor\ncommittee nre arranging their campaign\nIn Chicago, having gathered from all\npart* of the country evidence ranging\nfrom disproportionate Incronao In pay\nwhich aome railroad worker* have re-\nreived, to fact* and figure* which tend\nto prove that the high cost of living la\nbeginning to decline. The deereaso they i\nwill claim should he accompanied by a J\nproportionate decrease all along the\nline. 1\nW. W. Atterbury of the Fennayl-\nContinued on Twentieth Pag*.\nST. P15TKR SIM'RO, HRl.f.RAIK. TAMPA, I S\nSARASOTA and all Florida West Const resorts.\n2:0o P. M. and <1:20 P. M. dally. Short- j f\nrat route. No extra fare. Seaboard Air Line i\nIty., 11 Si B'way. Tel. Mad. ?i. 1373.?Adv. t\nHE N:\nNEW YO\nMORGAN'S\nE FOR EMBASSY\ne New Tobk Hbkai.p.\nNew York Herald Bureau. I\nWuahlnglon, D. C.. Jan. M.\ntates Government of the former\n1 as a residence for the American\njuae to-day sitting as a committee\nin allowing a section of the diplo ill\nto pass without objection and\na subject to approval or rejection\nications are no objections will be\nhe acceptance could have been\nof order, but apparently the proapproval\nof House members.\nbefore Congress for almost two\nPresident Wilson in a message to\nepartment in a communication to\nse. The Senate Foreign Relations\nlution authorizing acceptance, but\ni in favor of the provision of the\n,ing the name purpose.\nin charge of the diplomatic bill,\nleasure to the House commended\nid said it should mark the becrin\npurchase embassies or homes for\nappropriation in the same bill of\nlerican embassy at Paris,\nis at Prince's Gate and has been\nee generations. It is best rememic\nhome of the great art treasures\nle donor of the house to America.\nCALL 30.000 BACK\nTO MOTOR PIMi\nFord and Five Others Will lie\nsume on Fifty Per Cent.\nProduction Basis.\nWILL START ON MONDA1\nShutdown Was to- Reduc\nPrices of Supplies, Not\nWages, Is Belief.\nSpecial ZJespatrh to Thb N?w Yobk Hecali\nDKTitorr, Jan. 29.?Officials of si:\nfactories engaged in the manufactur\nof automobile accessories or bodies an\nnounced to-day that they would b\noperating Monday on a 50 per cenl\nproduction basis, with half of the for\nmcr working force, a total of mor\nthan 30,000 men, at their labors.\nThe factories are: Hudson Moto\nCar Company. Cadillac Motor Ca\nCompany, Ford Motor Car Companj\nStandard Motor Truck Companj\nFisher Body Company and the Brlgg\nManufacturing Company.\nThe announcement that the For\nCompany would reopen probably on\n50 per cent, basis has had a stlmulatlni\nsffect on the entire motor trade, am\nparticularly among makers of For\njodles and accessorlea\nThe Brlggs company, makers of Fori\njodies. announced to-day that Its work\nncn would be rehired Monday.\nWorking forces of the Hudson. Stand\nird Motor Truck, Cadillac and Flshe\nBody companies have been increasei\nifnvdually during this week and wll\neach a 50 per cent, basis Monday, off!\nlals of the firms reported.\nAt most of the plants all former em\nployees. regardless of marital status, ar\nbeing recalled. But In some, lncludlni\nthe Cadillac, operation will be begun oi\na three day a week schedule.\nOfficials of the Columbia Motor Com\npany stated that 25 per cent of tliel\nnormal working force were employe*\nasi week and that \"It orders keep coin\nng In the way they have during th<\naat three or four days\" production an*\nemployment would rise to 35 to 40 pe\nsent of normal during the first weel\nof February.\nThirty-five per cent, of tho Hudsoi\nCompany's employeee are at work. Pro\nAuction experts of the plant stated tha\njprlng orders were encouraging enougl\nto Indicate an lncreaso In both outpu\nur.d employment to 70 per cent, of nor\nmal In four weeks.\nApproximately 26 per cent, of the em\nployees of the Liberty Motor Compan:\n?re at work. Production of motor truck\nhas decreased slightly, but there Is ai\nIncreased demand for pleasure car en\nglnes. according to an official of tb<\nContinental Motor Corporation. Abou\n10 per cent, of the normal force* Is a\nwork In the plant.\nSHIP BURNED AT SEA;\nLOSS OF UFE FEAREL\nBelgian Vessel Bringing Sur\nvivors; Some Burned.\nNkwport News, Vs., Jan. 29.?Wire\ness advices received here to-night wet*\nto the effect that the Italian ater.mshii\nNeptunla ?u burned at sea to-aay win\ni probable loss of life.\nThe Belgian steamship Kllmmar\nvound for Hampton Roads la brlngini\nthe surviving members of the crew sev\nril of whom are said to have beoi\nladfy burned. Quarantine officials a\n)ld Point Comfort have been naked t<\nneet the ship with doctora and nurses\nLONG BRANCH MAM DIES\nOF SLEEPING SICKNESi\n4 Second Stricken and it\nCritical Condition.\ntpeclal Despatch to Tiia New Toaa HaaAi.r\nTx)no Branch, S. J., Jan. 29.?Ucorg<\nk. Paralow, 69 years old, for twenty-flvi\nrears choir leader of St. Luke's Method\nst Episcopal Church, died to-day fron\nileeplnar sickness.\nKearnlc Reld, cashier of the Cltlseni\nS'attonal Bank of Long Branch, als<\nvas stricken to-day with sleeping sick\nicss. His condition Is said to be critical\nIKKKINB capital or do you wlsli Fo-maicTai\ninvestment? Turn to Papa 0, Hscond New\nlertlon, to-day'a Issue and not# the man;\nidverttssn-.ents under Business Opportunl\nles,?Adv.\nEW YC\n[COPYRIGHT, 1981, BY THE\nRK, SUNDAY, JANUARY\nKRAMER LOCKS UP\nRUM WAREHOUSES!\nIN SEVEN STATBSj\nDrastic Order Issued to\nfnrh Liniinr Ttinrr nnd\nHalt Bootlegging.\nEAST ONLY AFFECTED\nIndustrial Alcohol, Church\nWine and Druggists' Orders\nExcepted.\nSURPRISE IN NEW EDICT\nNot Until Stocks of Legal\nHolders'Become Low Will\nRuling Be Revoked.\nSpecial Dexpaich to Tub New York Herald.\nNew York Herald Bureau. I\nWaahlngton, D. C., Jan. 89. I\nAs a desperate measure to break the\nKastern rpm ring and stop Illicit traf\nflc In the so called wet belt of East~\nem States, Prohibition Commissioner\nKramer late to-day Issued stringent\norders closing all warehouses In New\nYork, Pennsylvania, New Jersey, Mary^\nland, Connecticut, Rhode Island and\nJ Massachusetts.\nJ The order came as a surprise and It\nwas intended to keep It secret until\nnews filtered fj-om one of the Maryi_\n.land warehouse centre* that instructions\nhad been received to stop all\nwithdrawals.\nOnly three exceptions are made. Industrial\nalcohol can be released on\nspecially approved permits, sacra[\nmental wines are entirely excepted,\nand provision is made that each licensed\nretail druggist can draw a\ne maximum of five cases of whiskey on\na single permit.\nOne direct effect desired is the withholding\nof supplies from the manufacturers\nof patented medicines, tonics and\nother orenarationsi whlnh. Hav?\nthe market and tho stopping of wlthx\ndrawal of any considerable shipment of\nwhiskey or other spirit commonly used\nfor beverage. The order limiting -withdrawals\nIs designed to drive Illicit deal?\ners from the market as a necessary first\nt. step to amy kind of enforcement.\nCase Shipments Only.\n6 Shipments to druggists will in futuro\nbe made In case lots, obviating losses\nr from barrels, and any tssuonce of wine,\n,I> except for sacramental purposes, gin\nr and rum will be totopped Indefinitely.\nj The order will not be revoked ufttll\nstocks of all authorized users of spirits\n8 arc at an absolute minimum. Meantime\nIt Is hoped that bootleggers will be dljil\ncouraged.\na Freight handlers and express employIt\nees are blamed by the prohibition dlvld\nalon of the Treasury for numerous cases\nd of watered wdiiskey received and sold\nby druggists and others authorized 10\n1 handle spirits for legal ude.\nHundreds of complaints have come to\nthe Revenue Bureau from persons hav\nIng prescriptions filled? and In many lnr\nstances from druggists and other II1\ncensed purveyors of whiskey that tho\nd supply was hatered or otherwise dllutcxl.\nIn many Instances just plain water\nwas added to otherwise good whiskey.\nIn other cases alcohol and other sub\nr stances have been put !n frequently, ut- s\nterly spoiling the product. Chief Young'\nn of the withdrawal division of the Prohibition\nUnit stated emphatically to-day\nthat all whiskey withdrawn from warer\nhouses on permit was gauged and tested\n1 for tax purposes immediately before\nwithdrawal and had to be pure. The\namount of tax paid is dependent on the\nnumber of proof gallons In the barrel.\nProof gallons are the measure of alcop\nhollc content. For Instance, whiskey that\nc la 100 proof has 80 per cent, aloohol and\n60 per cent, of other substances, mostly\ni water. It must be 100 proof when with\ndrawn.\nt Chaaees for Liquor Thefts.\n1 Shipments of withdrawn spirits are\nmade under bond, but many auch shlp\nment* lay In express and freight offices\nfor days before Anally claimed or dcllv\nored. After they are received at deaIr\ntinatlon, way bills apd permits must be\nt vised and approved by local prohibition\nofficers before delivery c^n be made by\nthe railroad or express office.\nIt la alleged that somewhere along\ne the line employees or others having ac\nt mm to railroad or express property\nt drill holes In barrels or kpock out\nbungs, siphon off some liquor, fill up\nwith water and plug the containers.\nA general watch has been started on\nall shipments In transit In future It\nj Is likely they will be gauged not only\nupon leaving the warehouse but on de>\nlivery at destination so that the point\nof loaa can be ascertained.\nCOPS SEIZE ALCOHOL\nAND FIND IT WATER\nOfficials Shocked at Discovery\nat Ossining.\nI Frank MInneriy. Chief of Police at\nOssining, was walking down the main\nstreet of that town yesterday when he\nwas hailed by I'hlllp Fleck, a trustee\nof Osajntqg llospltal.\n1 \"Frank,\" said Trustee Fleck, as they\nwent on down the street, \"You don't\nhappen to know any one who has some\nalcohol for sale, do you?\"'\nAny one who knows Chief MInneriy\nContinued on Second Page.\nI _\nTo the Ur,\nand ikoM aaakin)\nRefer to the Help Wa\nTHE NEW Y(\nSEE 3ECTIOM\nAnd do not overlook th\nment Ajrencies for he\nA\na\n>RK H\nSDN-HERALD CORPORATION.\nr OA 1 QOl ENTERED A8 SEC\nOV, 1O?X. I'OBT OFFICE.\n\nDniester's Right Bank\nBlockaded by Rumania\n\"yiENNA, Jan. 29.?The Rumanian\nGovernment has declared\nthe right bank of the Dniester to\nbe in a state of siege and has\nprohibited all traffic in that region,\naccording to a Bucharest\ndespatch received here to-day.\nNINE DE IN FIRE\nIN HOBOKEN HOTEL\nList May Be Doubled in Blazt\nThat Destroyed PalaceColonial.\nMANY WOMEN KESCUEI\nSmoke and Flames Cut Ofl\nFiremen From Upper Floors,\nWhere Victims Were.\n'Nino persons lost their lives and 1'\nIs believed that the death list may b<\nIncreased to twice that number In\nfire that destroyed the Palace-Colonla\nHotel, In Newark street, a block and i\nhalf from the Lackawanna Rallroac\nstation In Hoboken early this morn\ning.\nAt 2 o'clock flames still were sweeping\nthrough the rear part of the hotel, ant\nfiremen believed that the rooms on th<\nsecond and third floors still contained\nbodies. The blaze there was so lntenst\nthey had not been ablo to get intt\nany of the rooms.\nBesides those found dead at least foui\npersons were so badly burned that aftci\nthey hid been rescued from top flooi\nrooms they were hurried to hospitals\nwhera It was said their condition wai\nsuch that they may die. At least f\ndozen others, many of them women\nwere found partly overcome In rooms or\nthe upper floors and were carried dowr\nladders and fire escapes to the street\nThey v. ere for the most part wlthou'\nanything but night clothes.\nThe fire is believed to have startec\nfrom a cigarette butt In a linen room\nClerks said that when the flames wen\ndiscovered about forty persons were lr\nthe five story brick building.\nThe fire spread with remarkable rapid\nity. It was not known who turned ii\nthe first alarm, but the signal bell In th<\nbox on a corner nearby was still ringing\nwhen the first apparatus reached th>\nscene from fire headquarters, two block!\naway.\nAt that tlnio the entire building was it\nflames and filled with smoke. Men am\nwomen were hanging from windows ant\nthreatening to drop Into the streets ai\nthe firemen began to raise their laddort\nThe Rev. Edward Kelly, Catholh\nchaplain of the Hoboken Fire Department,\narrived with the apparatus on the\nsecond alarm and as soon as the fire\nhad been driven to the rear of the\nbuilding entered at the head of a searching\nparty to look for Injured and dying\nFiremen said the priest admlnisteret\nthe last rites of the church to persom\nwho were dying from bums and then\nhelped carry them to the street.\nAdjoining the building Is that of the\nFirst National Bank of Hoboken. While\nI the blase was at its height the police,\nfearing on attempt might be made to\nrob the bank, placed guards at doore\nand windows and posted others on the\nroof.\nMost of the bodies were found on the\ntwo upper floors. A man and a woman\nwere foujid burned to death In one room\nand a woman's body was found on the\nfloor of an adjoining room. Apparently\nthose who lost their lives were overcome\nby smoke which swept quickly to one\nupper floor, and then were cut off from\nrescue by the flames, e^ilch spread\nthrough the second floor from the liner\nroom, making It Impossible for the 'firemen\nto make their way upstairs.\nNone of tho victims hud been Identl\nf ed early this morning:.\n42 TO as YEARS IN CELL\nFOR YOUTHFUL FIREBUG\nBoy of 19 Caused $2,000,000\nDamage in Two Months.\nf-prrial Detpatch to Tm New York Hciui.d.\nFniontown, Pa.. Jan. 29.?Pleading\nguilty to thlrteo ncharges of arson in\nconnection with the wave of incendiarism\nwhich spread over Fayette county\nfor more than two months, Albert Smith,\n19 years old. son of Reuben Smith,\nwealthy Fnlr Hope real estate operator,\nwas sentenced to-day by Judge J. Q\nVan Swearlngen to serve forty-two to\nI elghty-flve years in the Western Penitentiary.\ni \"I Intend this shall be a life sentence,\"\nthe court said In Imposing Judgment\nIt was the longest sentence given here\n1 since 1890. when a man charged with\nI assault got forty-five years.\nHis sentence to-day was the final\nchapter in the sensational story ol\nburned schoolhousea. churches, barns,\nHuainaaa hmiar-a and Drlvale residence-,\nwith entailed losses upwnrd of >2.000.000.\nAsserting that two of Smith's uncles\nj now are Inmates of asylums. Patterson\nasked that sentence be deferred until\nj medical esperts could make an esamina'\ntlon nnd determine whether the boy\nshould be sent to prison or an asylum.\nRILLED I!* TRAIN WBKCK.\nOodkn. Jan. 29.?Morris Ferguson, a\nUnion Pacific employee of Oakland, Ind.,\nI was killed and eleven persons were *iiJured.\nsome seriously, when an east\nbound Union Pacific freight train\ncrashed Into the rear end of a work\nI train between Knight and Altamom\nWyo., last night.\nlemployed\nI batter positions\nnted advertisement* in J\n3RK HERALD j;\nI SIX TO-DAY\nie offerings of EmployIp\nof the better kind.\nV ?sJI\ns^rrrrrJ\n[ERAL\ni\nOND CRABS MATTER. p A\nNEVV YORK. N. Y.\nKING ALBERT PUTS\nUP GUP FOR RACE ji\nI ACROSS ATLANTIC\nI\nContest Set for July f Open\nto Sailing Yachts of\nthe World.\nI\nFROM HERE TO OSTEND\nAuxiliary Craft Mav Com\npete if Engines Are Sealed\nor Neutralized.\n\nREVIVAL WINS APPROVAL\nr\nLast Event of Its Kind for\nKaiser's^Cup, Which Turned\nOut to lie Pewter.\nt\nAlbert, King of the Belgians, yestcr-\n1 day offered a gold cup for an ocean j\n1 race next summer from Sandy Hook\n1 to Ostend, open to sailing yachts of'\nthe world. The announcement was\nmade by Baron de Cartier de Mar- 1\nchienne, Belgian Ambassador to the\nUnited States. Under the conditions\n1 approved by the King, the race Is to\nbe for the championship of the high\n1 seas without handicap and open to\nall sizes, types and rigs. Auxiliary\nyachts are eligible, provided the propelling\nmachinery is sealed or neur\ntralized before the start,\nr The start is to be at noon July 4.\nr without postponement, regardless of\nwind or weather, and the starting\n1 point will be Ambrose Channel light 1\nvessel, where the races for the Amerj\nica's Cup started last summer. A\nwarning signal will be given ten mln.\nutes before noon and boats unable by\nt reason of fog or calm to reach tlu\nstarting line will be penalized for time\n1 lost.\nThe finish will be off Ostend on the\nBelgian coast, where King Albert in\nperson will welcome the winner. Baron\nno <..aruer win asa one niemoer oacn\n1 from tlio New York, Atlantic and\ns Parchment yacht clubs to act as start?\ning committee. Entries will be res\n\ncelvetl by Pierre Mali, Belgian ConsulGeneral\nIn New York, at 25 Madison\navenue'.\n1\nj I.not Hncc in 1DOR.\n9 \"His Majesty desires that this race\ni. he an actual championship race f6r the i\nsupremacy of the seas.\" Baron de Car- j\ntier said, \"and therefore the arbitrary\nconditions for the start have been de- j\nJ elded upon. Particulars regarding the\nfinish off Ostend will be announced\nlater. King Albert's cup will become i\nthe permanent property of the winner 1\nand a suitable commemorative medal j\ni will be presented to each of the con- j\nl testants.\"\nEach member of the starting com-\nmlttee will represent his club exclu'\nsively. The. duty of the committee w.H\nbe to conduct the acttial starting and\ni consider any protests or fouls that may j\ni arise before the starting signal, at 1\nwhich time Its duties cease.\nThe last race across the Atlantic was\ni sailed In 1905 for a cup offered by the\ni German Kntser. Kleven boats entered\nand the winner was the Atlantic, >i\nI three masted schooner. 1S5 fe?t over all, I\nI then the property of Wilson Marshall,\ni rormer commoaore 01 mg L.arcnmoiii\nYacht Club.\ni Commodore Marshall's only son. an\nI American aviator, was killed during the\nwar. Shortly after he offered the\nKaiser'a \"solid gold cup\" to the lied 1\nCross, but when It was broken up It\nproved to be a gold plated pewter mug\nworth only a few hundred dollars, not\none-hundredth of the amount spent by\neach of the yachtsmen who competed\nfor It.\nThe Atlantic Is now owned by\nNicholas F. and James Cox Hrady.\nI She was In commission last summer\nand ahe may start In the race for King\nAlbert's cup. Her owners are out of\ntown and could not be reached ye