,Jan. 29.?At\nthe instance of Senator\nKnox, Republican, Pennsylvania,\nthe Senate stopped wrangling\nover emergency tariff proposals\nlong enough to-day to adopt an\namendment to the alien property\nact, so the wife of Count von\nBernstorff cannot get back her\n\\raluables from the Alien Property\nCustodian while the property\nof daughters of Henry White,;\nAmerican commissioner to the\npeace conference, is held.\nSenator Knox thus described\nthe situation, saying under the\nact an American born woman 1\nmarried to an enemy alien prior\nto the war could retain her prop-\nerty, while the daughter of\nAmerican parents, born abroad,\nand married to an enemy alien, I\nwas classed as an enemy alien\n^nerseii. 11\nHARD FIGHT AHEADj\nON TRANSIT BUS!\ni\ni\nMeasures Backed by Governor\nto Be Offered on Merit\nA lone.\nREADY IX TEX DAYS;\nJ\nSupport of City Senators Expected\nBefore Legislative\nVotes.\nSptcial Vespatrh to The New Yobk Hebai.d.\nNew York Herald lliirci.ii,\nAlbany, Jan. 2?.\nGov. Miller's plan' for saving New 1\nYork city's transit system from \"the i\nscrap heap or bankruptcy\" is being I\npushed forward with all the speed\npossible. The legislative leaders have\nbegun work on the bills which will\nembody and carry out the Executive's\nIdeas and the bill drafting bureau will\nhave the measures ready for presentation\nin about ten days.\nThere are to be two bills. One will\nsupplement the rapid transit act and\nthe other will amend the public service\nlaw. It Is a difficult task to draft\nsuch measures because of the necessity\nof conforming to court rulings made in\nrecent years on numerous points, and\nat the .same time to revamp tho law\nfind make it sufficiently flexible to meet\nthe new situation.\nA Storm of ConlroTenr.\nOne measure will adjust the State\nlaws, bringing them up to date. That\nwill take into consideration the subway\ncontracts and straighten out kinks in\nthe several laws. Another measure will\ncreate the new Public Service Commission,\nlodging in its hands the transit\npowers now resting 1th the Public Ser-<\nvice Commission, some of the authority\nof the Board of Estimate and the Jurisdiction\nof the transit commission.\nEven before the bills are ready and\ntheir real purpose understood thoroughly\nthe storm of controversy which hss\nbroken through the State on the whole\nsubject has aroused tfie legislature and\nthe party leaders as has no other conflict\nIn recent years.\nIn spite of the Governor's repeated\nassurance that tho question 13 not\nwhether a five or six cent fare shall j\nbe charged, the opposition is straining\nto the limit to set up that scarecrow\nbefore the Legislature. The first spasm\nof fear which somewhat alarmed the\nleaders last week has begun to subside.\nIn Its place is coming the demand that\nthe subject be treated on Its merits,\nrhe Governor's calmness in the face of\nthe uproar and his assurance that the\npublic will indorse his plan when It is\ntnderetood and robbed of its misrepre- I\nlentatlon. has steadied the Legislature, j\nBut there Is no doubt that there is 1\nI urnui: iiriii aiicxi. iv toum.cn..,\njo the most bitterly contested battle\n<tag?d In the legislature since the bills\nsere passed to regulate horse racing.\nAs It now stands, the situation Is New\nk'ork city against up-State. In the first\nrush to take sides, the New York delegation\nIn the Senate and Assembly\nflocked Into one corner regardless of i\njolltlcs or any other consideration. Their\nindvrstandlng use that the Issue was j\n:o bo a cleancut contest on whether j\nilgher fares should be voted, and on\nhat they were a unit against an In-\n:rease.\nI'lanatr Seems Assured.\nnut the reaction appears to have set!\nn. The announcement made by Jacob I\nV Livingston, Kings county Republican\ne.uler, that he Indorsed unqualifiedly\nhe Oovernor's position, and the partial\nipproval given by the Manhattan lead- i\nsrs have begun to have effect.\nIt Is the opinion of the leader* here|\nind of observers on the side lines that\nhe Oovernor's bills will past*. Every\nnan In the legislature will have to go\nin record and every possible Influence\nfor and against the proposals will be\nirougnt Into action In the next few\n*eek*.\nThe New York delegation In the Senile\nnumbers twenty-three, of whom\nwelve sic Republicans, ten Democrats\nmd one n Soda Hot The Democrats and\nSocialist will fight to the flnl?h against i\nhi' Mils, without much doubt Of the 1\nwelve Republican* nix represent Brookyn.\nthr?c Manhattan and one each\n?pe?lt for The Bronx Quoena and Rich-!\nuond. With the Republican organlgnlon*\nbacking the Governor, the suptorters\nof the plan are confident the\nlelegatlon will break up before the vote\n;otnoa aeveral wi eke hence. It would i\ntot be surprising wore the <1overnor to\nr\"t at leant three or four city votea In\nhe Mennte.\nIn the Assembly the altuntlon la much\nhe same New Tork and Kings country\neach has twenty-throe Assemblynen.\nThe Bronx eight, Queena six and\nRichmond two, making the total for the\nIty In the lower house sixty-two. There\nire fifteen Republican Senators from\nKings and thirteen from Manhattan.\nA'lth the county organisations of then*\nContinued on Rrcond rn.gr.\nghlto sulphur Springs Tito Oroonbrlor for\nrsst and ret ups ration. Bookings Flaia.-Are.\nIN ITS HISTORY. -1\nHerald, with all that was\nintertwined with it, and\nized, is a bigger and better\nrepaper than ever before.\npp\\TrPC\" In JlMluttoii. Brooklyn and\nvEili AO j Bronx. W?rwhfr? 10 Cent..\nlaO.P.imATORS\nDODGE TAMMANY'S\nCHEAP FARES TRAP\n[New Yorkers in Conference\nWith Koenig Discuss Gov.\nMiller's Message 011\nTransit Deform.\nNOT A POLITICAL GAME\nSnap Judgment Deprecated\non Plans to Put City's\nxracnon system on a\nBusiness Basis.\nAPPROVED BY HAUKXESS\nAuthor of Dual Contract for\nSubways Says Programme\nWill Correct Underlying\nFaults of Traction.\nRepublican leaders and members of\nthe Legislature from New York city\ndo not intend to permit Democratic\npoliticians or demagogues to badger\nthem into taking hasty action on the\nproposals for a solution of the transit\nproblem In this city as set forth by\nGov. Miller in his message.\nTheir desire is to stand behind Gov.\nMiller's programme, and so far as the\ntraction proposal is concerned they\nwill use their influence to have lh?\nbills drawn In such a way us to meet\nsome objections that have been raised\nby the opposition.\nThis decision was reached at a meeting\nof the Republican Senators and\nAssemblymen from New York county\nwith Samuel S. Koenig, the leader, at\nheadquarters yesterday afternoon.\nThere was no meeting in Brooklyn,\nbut the leaders there Bald their at- j\ntitude was similar to that in New Y'ork\ncounty. Three of the Senators ex- i\npressed themselves as against an increased\nfare.\nj \"Gov. Miller is endeavoring to ap\nply statesmanship instead of politics\nby reaching down and correcting tho\nj underlying difficulties,\" declared Le\nRoy T. Harkness, who, as counsel,\ndrafted the dual subway contracts for\nthe Public Service Commission, and M\nconsidered one of the best Informed\ntraction experts in the city.\nTrying to Make Political (sane.\nFollowing the lead of Tammany Hall,\nJohn H. McCoocv, Democratic leader In\ni Brooklyn, has called his executive committee\nand members of the Legislature\nto meet at 11 o'clock to-morrow morning.\nThey will leave nothing undone to\nmake political capital out of Gov. Miller's\nmessage. The legislators later will\ngo to tbe meeting of Democratic lawmakers,\narranged t?y Senator James J.\nWalker for noon at the City Halt. Ha\nhas Invited Republican members of the\nLegislature to attend, but the chances\nare that none will appear.\nIt was reported that some of ihe\nDemocratic leaders in Brooklyn had expressed\nthemselves privately in favor\nof Gov Miller's proposal, but at the\nsame time chuckled at the way they\nintended to use It for political effect\nagainst the Republicans.\nThe public forum furnished hy th<?\nLeague for Political Education nil! t\nmeet In the Town Hall, in West Forty-\nthird street, to-morrow night for a discussion\nof Gov. Miller's transit programme.\nThe genera! public is Invited.\nJob E. Hedges and Oliver C. Scmple will\nsupport the affirmative side of the\nquestion, while H. H. Curran, Boroggh\nPresident of Manhattan, and another\nspeaker will argue for a greater measure\nof home rule. It Is announced that\n\"every man, woman and child who attends\nthe gathering will be allowed to\nexpress his views on the present transit\nsituation here.\"\nIn line with their policy the New\nYork county legislators refused to discuss\ntheir meeting or Indicate the line\nof argument that went on for mors\nthan two hours. An innocuous statement\nwas Issued saying It was one of\nthe regular weekly meetings to discuss\nmatters pending in the Legislature.\nAmong the \"matters\" was the \"transit\nsituation In New York city.\"\n\"It was the unanimous opinion of\nthose pfesent,\" the statement read,\n\"that tho most careful consideration\nand study be given to those matters\nnartlcularlv affecting the city of New\nYork. The members will meet nest\nSaturday afternoon.\"'\nTransit la Dlaensscd Kreely.\nWith the legislator* were their A*? i\nrembly dlatrlct leader* and former Sena*\ntor Albert Ottlnger, chairman of the\ncommittee on State legislation rf the j\ncounty committee, ard Courtlandt Nlcoll,\nchairman of the committee on city af?\nfalrn of the National Ilcpuhllean Club,\nit 1* understood the lawmaker* and\nl?adera expressed themselve* freely In\nregard to the aentlment In their district*\nand discussed way* In which the billa to\ncarry out Oov. Miller's message could\nbe framed *o a* to do away with the\nprotest* that have he? n made against\nsome of hi* proposal*.\nThe legislators were advised not to.\ncommit themselves until the bills had\nbeen put In flr.al shape, when they could\ntalk Intelligently --n the subject. It was\nagreed to use the Influence of the united\ndelegation from New York city toward\nobtaining certain modification* or Inter*\nprobations of the programme\n\"A message Is not s bill,\" said one of\nthe leader*. \"Nor Is snap judgment on\na message a true measure of what people\nwill really think of It aft*r they ha\\<?\nhad a i-hance to study It. The Governor\nalreadv ha* elucidated hie Idea* by sup.\nplemcntal statements since his meaaago\nsi ?.i m-i hsbi mtiin u wv\\n\nthrough service rtelly. .VI*nil\" Coast Line,\nOffice, 1246 B way. Tel. Longacre 5M3.?Aitr,","height":"24168","width":"19398"}}
